#### Arts and culture

For a comprehensive overview, consult the article on the [Culture of Los Angeles](/Culture_of_Los_Angeles).

The historic center of the city, located at [Plaza de Los Ángeles](/Los_Angeles_Plaza) near [Calle Olvera](/Olvera_Street).

Los Angeles is frequently heralded as the world's creative capital, with one in every six residents employed in a creative industry. &#91;210&#93; The city is home to more artists, writers, filmmakers, actors, dancers, and musicians than any other city in history. &#91;211&#93; Los Angeles culture is significantly influenced by Mexican American heritage, a legacy of California's history as part of Mexico and, prior to that, the Spanish Empire. &#91;212&#93; The city is also renowned for its prolific [murals](/Murals_of_Los_Angeles). &#91;213&#93;

##### Landmarks

For related lists, see [List of sites of interest in the Los Angeles area](/List_of_sites_of_interest_in_the_Los_Angeles_area) and [National Register of Historic Places listings in Los Angeles, California](/National_Register_of_Historic_Places_listings_in_Los_Angeles,_California).

[El Cabrillo](/El_Cabrillo), an example of [Spanish Revival](/Spanish_Colonial_Revival) architecture and a [National Historic Landmark](/National_Historic_Landmark).

The architectural landscape of Los Angeles reflects its historical influences, drawing from Spanish, Mexican, and American traditions. Popular architectural styles found throughout the city include [Spanish Colonial Revival](/Spanish_Colonial_Revival), [Mission Revival](/Mission_Revival), [California Churrigueresque](/California_Churrigueresque), [Mediterranean Revival](/Mediterranean_Revival), [Art Deco](/Art_Deco_architecture), and [Mid-Century Modern](/Mid-century_modern), among others.

Key landmarks in Los Angeles include the iconic [Hollywood Sign](/Hollywood_Sign), &#91;214&#93; the [Walt Disney Concert Hall](/Walt_Disney_Concert_Hall), the distinctive [Capitol Records Building](/Capitol_Records_Building), &#91;215&#93; the [Cathedral of Our Lady of the Angels](/Cathedral_of_Our_Lady_of_the_Angels), &#91;216&#93; the historic [Angels Flight](/Angels_Flight) railway, &#91;217&#93; [Grauman's Chinese Theatre](/Grauman%27s_Chinese_Theatre), &#91;218&#93; the [Dolby Theatre](/Dolby_Theatre), &#91;219&#93; the renowned [Griffith Observatory](/Griffith_Observatory), &#91;220&#93; the [Getty Center](/Getty_Center) and its sister institution, the [Getty Villa](/Getty_Villa), &#91;221&#93; &#91;222&#93; the architecturally significant [Stahl House](/Stahl_House), &#91;223&#93; the historic [Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum](/Los_Angeles_Memorial_Coliseum), the vibrant entertainment complex of [L.A. Live](/L.A._Live), &#91;224&#93; the [Los Angeles County Museum of Art](/Los_Angeles_County_Museum_of_Art), the unique [Venice Canal Historic District](/Venice_Canal_Historic_District) and its famous boardwalk, the futuristic [Theme Building](/Theme_Building), the architecturally acclaimed [Bradbury Building](/Bradbury_Building), the towering [U.S. Bank Tower](/U.S._Bank_Tower), the modern [Wilshire Grand Center](/Wilshire_Grand_Center), the bustling [Hollywood Boulevard](/Hollywood_Boulevard), the civic landmark [Los Angeles City Hall](/Los_Angeles_City_Hall), the iconic [Hollywood Bowl](/Hollywood_Bowl), &#91;225&#93; the decommissioned battleship USS Iowa, the distinctive [Watts Towers](/Watts_Towers), &#91;226&#93; the popular [Crypto.com Arena](/Crypto.com_Arena), the historic [Dodger Stadium](/Dodger_Stadium), and the culturally significant [Olvera Street](/Olvera_Street). &#91;227&#93;

##### Movies and the performing arts

Further information is available on the [Music of Los Angeles](/Music_of_Los_Angeles). Related lists include [List of films set in Los Angeles](/List_of_films_set_in_Los_Angeles) and [List of songs about Los Angeles](/List_of_songs_about_Los_Angeles).

[Grauman's Chinese Theatre](/Grauman%27s_Chinese_Theatre) on the illustrious [Hollywood Walk of Fame](/Hollywood_Walk_of_Fame).

The performing arts play a pivotal role in defining the cultural identity of Los Angeles. According to the USC Stevens Institute for Innovation, the city hosts "more than 1,100 annual theatrical productions and 21 openings every week." &#91;211&#93; The [Los Angeles Music Center](/Los_Angeles_Music_Center) is recognized as "one of the three largest performing arts centers in the nation," attracting over 1.3 million visitors annually. &#91;228&#93; The architectural marvel that is the [Walt Disney Concert Hall](/Walt_Disney_Concert_Hall), the centerpiece of the Music Center, serves as the home of the esteemed [Los Angeles Philharmonic]. &#91;229&#93; Resident companies at the Music Center also include notable organizations such as the [Center Theatre Group](/Center_Theatre_Group), the [Los Angeles Master Chorale](/Los_Angeles_Master_Chorale), and the [Los Angeles Opera](/Los_Angeles_Opera). &#91;230&#93; &#91;231&#93; &#91;232&#93; The cultivation of artistic talent is fostered at premier institutions like the [Colburn School](/Colburn_School) and the [USC Thornton School of Music](/USC_Thornton_School_of_Music).

The [Hollywood Bowl](/Hollywood_Bowl) in the scenic [Hollywood Hills](/Hollywood_Hills).

The [Hollywood neighborhood](/Hollywood,_Los_Angeles) of Los Angeles has long been recognized as the epicenter of the [motion picture industry](/Film_industry), a distinction it has held since the early 20th century. The Los Angeles area is also synonymous with being the hub of the [television industry](/Television_industry). &#91;233&#93; The city hosts major film studios as well as prominent record labels. Los Angeles is the venue for prestigious annual awards ceremonies, including the [Academy Awards](/Academy_Awards), the [Primetime Emmy Awards](/Primetime_Emmy_Awards), and the [Grammy Awards](/Grammy_Awards), alongside numerous other accolades within the entertainment sector. The city is home to the [USC School of Cinematic Arts](/USC_School_of_Cinematic_Arts), which holds the distinction of being the oldest film school in the United States. &#91;234&#93;

##### Museums and galleries

For related lists, see [List of museums in Los Angeles](/List_of_museums_in_Los_Angeles) and [List of museums in Los Angeles County, California](/List_of_museums_in_Los_Angeles_County,_California).

The [Getty Villa](/Getty_Villa), one of two campuses belonging to the [J. Paul Getty Museum](/J._Paul_Getty_Museum), alongside the [Getty Center](/Getty_Center).

Los Angeles County, California, is home to 841 museums and art galleries, with a significant concentration located within the city of Los Angeles itself. &#91;235&#93; This impressive number signifies more museums per capita than any other city in the U.S. &#91;235&#93; Among the notable institutions are the [Los Angeles County Museum of Art](/Los_Angeles_County_Museum_of_Art), recognized as the largest art museum in the Western United States, &#91;236&#93; the [Getty Center](/Getty_Center), which is part of the [J. Paul Getty Trust](/J._Paul_Getty_Trust), the world's wealthiest art institution, &#91;237&#93; the [Petersen Automotive Museum], &#91;238&#93; the [Huntington Library], &#91;239&#93; the [Natural History Museum](/Natural_History_Museum_of_Los_Angeles_County), &#91;240&#93; the historic [Battleship Iowa], &#91;241&#93; [The Broad](/The_Broad), which houses an extensive collection of over 2,000 works of contemporary art, &#91;242&#93; and the [Museum of Contemporary Art, Los Angeles](/Museum_of_Contemporary_Art,_Los_Angeles). &#91;243&#93; A substantial number of art galleries are situated along [Gallery Row], where tens of thousands of visitors attend the monthly Downtown Art Walk. &#91;244&#93;

#### Libraries

The [Los Angeles Public Library](/Los_Angeles_Public_Library) system operates a network of 72 public libraries across the city. &#91;245&#93; Certain unincorporated areas within the county are served by branches of the [County of Los Angeles Public Library](/County_of_Los_Angeles_Public_Library), many of which are conveniently located within walking distance for local residents. &#91;246&#93;

#### Cuisine

For a list of acclaimed dining establishments, see [List of Michelin-starred restaurants in California](/List_of_Michelin-starred_restaurants_in_California).

The culinary landscape of Los Angeles is a vibrant fusion of global flavors, a direct result of the city's rich immigrant history and diverse population. As of 2025, the [Michelin](/Michelin) Guide has recognized 20 starred restaurants within the city, including [Providence](/Providence_(restaurant)) and [Somni](/Somni), both of which have earned the prestigious three Michelin stars. &#91;247&#93;

Immigrants from Latin America, particularly those from [Mexico](/Mexican_cuisine), have introduced a wealth of culinary traditions, including [tacos](/Taco), [burritos](/Burrito), [quesadillas](/Quesadilla), [tortas](/Torta), [tamales](/Tamale), and [enchiladas]. These dishes are readily available from food trucks and street stands, as well as from specialized [taquerias](/Taqueria) and [cafés](/Caf%C3%A9). Asian culinary influences are also prominent, with numerous immigrant-owned restaurants scattered throughout the city, particularly in vibrant culinary hubs like [Chinatown](/Chinatown), &#91;248&#93; [Koreatown](/Koreatown,_Los_Angeles), &#91;249&#93; and [Little Tokyo](/Little_Tokyo,_Los_Angeles). &#91;250&#93; Furthermore, Los Angeles offers an exceptional array of vegan, vegetarian, and plant-based dining options.

#### Sports

For a comprehensive overview, consult the article on [Sports in Los Angeles](/Sports_in_Los_Angeles). Related topics include [Soccer in Los Angeles](/Soccer_in_Los_Angeles) and [History of the National Football League in Los Angeles](/History_of_the_National_Football_League_in_Los_Angeles).

The historic [Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum](/Los_Angeles_Memorial_Coliseum).

Los Angeles and its surrounding metropolitan area are home to eleven top-tier professional sports teams. While some of these teams are based in neighboring communities, they proudly carry "Los Angeles" in their names. These include the [Los Angeles Dodgers](/Los_Angeles_Dodgers) &#91;251&#93; and the [Los Angeles Angels](/Los_Angeles_Angels) &#91;252&#93; of [Major League Baseball](/Major_League_Baseball) (MLB); the [Los Angeles Rams](/Los_Angeles_Rams) &#91;253&#93; and [Los Angeles Chargers](/Los_Angeles_Chargers) of the [National Football League](/National_Football_League) (NFL); the [Los Angeles Lakers](/Los_Angeles_Lakers) &#91;254&#93; and [Los Angeles Clippers](/Los_Angeles_Clippers) &#91;255&#93; of the [National Basketball Association](/National_Basketball_Association) (NBA); the [Los Angeles Kings](/Los_Ang Angeles_Kings) &#91;256&#93; and [Anaheim Ducks](/Anaheim_Ducks) &#91;257&#93; of the [National Hockey League](/National_Hockey_League) (NHL); the [Los Angeles Galaxy](/Los_Angeles_Galaxy) &#91;258&#93; and [Los Angeles FC](/Los_Angeles_FC) &#91;259&#93; of [Major League Soccer](/Major_League_Soccer) (MLS); and the [Los Angeles Sparks](/Los_Angeles_Sparks) of the [Women's National Basketball Association](/Women%27s_National_Basketball_Association) (WNBA). &#91;260&#93; Additionally, the city is represented in [Minor League Cricket](/Minor_League_Cricket) (MiLC) by the [SoCal Lashings](/SoCal_Lashings) and in [Major League Cricket](/Major_League_Cricket) (MLC) by the [Los Angeles Knight Riders](/Los_Angeles_Knight_Riders). &#91;261&#93;

Other notable sports affiliations include the [UCLA Bruins](/UCLA_Bruins) and the [USC Trojans](/USC_Trojans), both prominent NCAA Division I teams competing in the [Big Ten Conference](/Big_Ten_Conference). &#91;262&#93;

[Dodger Stadium](/Dodger_Stadium), the home venue of the [Los Angeles Dodgers](/Los_Angeles_Dodgers) in [Major League Baseball](/Major_League_Baseball).

Despite being the second-largest city in the United States, Los Angeles notably did not host an NFL team between 1995 and 2015. &#91;History_of_the_National_Football_League_in_Los_Angeles&#93; For a period, the Los Angeles area was home to two NFL franchises: the Rams and the Raiders. Both teams relocated in 1995, with the Rams moving to [St. Louis](/St._Louis) and the Raiders returning to their original home in [Oakland, California](/Oakland,_California). After a 21-season tenure in St. Louis, the NFL announced on January 12, 2016, that the Rams would return to Los Angeles for the [2016 NFL season](/2016_NFL_season), playing their home games at the [Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum](/Los_Angeles_Memorial_Coliseum) for four seasons. &#91;263&#93; &#91;264&#93; &#91;265&#93; Prior to their move in 1995, the Rams had played their home games in the Coliseum from 1946 to 1979, making them the first professional sports team to establish residency in Los Angeles. They subsequently moved to [Anaheim Stadium](/Anaheim_Stadium) from 1980 to 1994. On January 12, 2017, the [San Diego Chargers](/San_Diego_Chargers) announced their intention to relocate back to Los Angeles, becoming the [Los Angeles Chargers](/Los_Angeles_Chargers) starting with the [2017 NFL season](/2017_NFL_season). They played their home games at [Dignity Health Sports Park](/Dignity_Health_Sports_Park) in [Carson, California](/Carson,_California) for three seasons. &#91;266&#93; Both the Rams and the Chargers subsequently moved to the newly constructed [SoFi Stadium](/SoFi_Stadium), located in nearby [Inglewood](/Inglewood,_California), beginning with the 2020 season. &#91;267&#93;

[Crypto.com Arena](/Crypto.com_Arena), the home venue for the [Los Angeles Lakers](/Los_Angeles_Lakers), [Los Angeles Kings](/Los_Angeles_Kings), and [Los Angeles Sparks](/Los_Angeles_Sparks).

Los Angeles boasts a number of prominent sports venues, including [Dodger Stadium](/Dodger_Stadium), &#91;268&#93; the [Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum](/Los_Angeles_Memorial_Coliseum), &#91;269&#93; [BMO Stadium](/BMO_Stadium) &#91;270&#93; and [Crypto.com Arena](/Crypto.com_Arena). &#91;271&#93; Additionally, venues such as the [Kia Forum](/Kia_Forum), SoFi Stadium, Dignity Health Sports Park, the [Rose Bowl](/Rose_Bowl_(stadium)), [Angel Stadium](/Angel_Stadium), [Honda Center](/Honda_Center), and [Intuit Dome](/Intuit_Dome) are located in adjacent cities and within the broader Los Angeles metropolitan area. &#91;272&#93;

Los Angeles has twice hosted the [Summer Olympic Games](/Summer_Olympic_Games), in [1932](/1932_Summer_Olympics) and [1984](/1984_Summer_Olympics), and is slated to host for a third time in [2028](/2028_Summer_Olympics). &#91;273&#93; This will make Los Angeles the third city, after London ([1908](/1908_Summer_Olympics), [1948](/1948_Summer_Olympics), and [2012](/2012_Summer_Olympics)) and Paris ([1900](/1900_Summer_Olympics), [1924](/1924_Summer_Olympics), and [2024](/2024_Summer_Olympics)), to host the Olympic Games on three occasions. Los Angeles has submitted 10 bids to host Olympic events to the [International Olympic Committee](/International_Olympic_Committee), more than any other city worldwide. &#91;274&#93; In commemoration of the tenth Olympic Games hosted in 1932, the former 10th Street was renamed Olympic Boulevard. Los Angeles also hosted the [Deaflympics](/Deaflympics) in [1985](/1985_Summer_Deaflympics) &#91;275&#93; and the [Special Olympics World Summer Games](/Special_Olympics_World_Games) in [2015](/2015_Special_Olympics_World_Summer_Games). &#91;276&#93;

[BMO Stadium](/BMO_Stadium), the home stadium for [Los Angeles FC](/Los_Angeles_FC) of [Major League Soccer](/Major_League_Soccer).

Eight NFL [Super Bowls](/Super_Bowl) have been held in the city and its surrounding areas: two at the Memorial Coliseum (including the inaugural [Super Bowl I](/Super_Bowl_I) and [Super Bowl VII](/Super_Bowl_VII)), five at the Rose Bowl in suburban [Pasadena, California](/Pasadena,_California) (Super Bowls [XI](/Super_Bowl_XI), [XIV](/Super_Bowl_XIV), [XVII](/Super_Bowl_XVII), [XXI](/Super_Bowl_XXI), and [XXVII](/Super_Bowl_XXVII)), and one at the suburban [Inglewood, California](/Inglewood,_California) (Super Bowl [LVI](/Super_Bowl_LVI)). &#91;277&#93; The Rose Bowl also hosts the annual and highly prestigious [NCAA](/NCAA) [college football](/College_football) game known as the [Rose Bowl Game](/Rose_Bowl_game), played every New Year's Day.

Los Angeles hosted eight [FIFA World Cup](/FIFA_World_Cup) soccer matches at the [Rose Bowl](/Rose_Bowl_(stadium)) in [1994](/1994_FIFA_World_Cup), including the [final match](/1994_FIFA_World_Cup_Final), where [Brazil](/Brazil_national_football_team) emerged victorious. The Rose Bowl also hosted four games during the [1999 FIFA Women's World Cup](/1999_FIFA_Women%27s_World_Cup), including the [final](/1999_FIFA_Women%27s_World_Cup_Final), in which the [United States](/United_States_women%27s_national_soccer_team) defeated [China](/China_women%27s_national_football_team) in a penalty shootout. This match is famously remembered for the iconic image of [Brandi Chastain](/Brandi_Chastain) celebrating her winning penalty kick. Los Angeles is designated as one of eleven U.S. host cities for the [2026 FIFA World Cup](/2026_FIFA_World_Cup), with matches scheduled to be played at [SoFi Stadium](/SoFi_Stadium). &#91;278&#93;

Los Angeles is one of only six North American cities to have achieved championships across all five of its major professional sports leagues (MLB, NFL, NHL, NBA, and MLS). This distinction was secured with the Kings' victory in the [2012 Stanley Cup Final](/2012_Stanley_Cup_Finals). &#91;279&#93;

#### Government

For a comprehensive overview, consult the article on the [Government of Los Angeles](/Government_of_Los_Angeles). Further details can be found in [List of elected officials in Los Angeles](/List_of_elected_officials_in_Los_Angeles), and related information is available in [Government of Los Angeles County](/Government_of_Los_Angeles_County).

The historic [Los Angeles City Hall](/Los_Angeles_City_Hall), constructed in 1928, serves as the seat of the [Mayor of Los Angeles](/Mayor_of_Los_Angeles) and the [Los Angeles City Council](/Los_Angeles_City_Council).

Los Angeles operates under a [charter city](/Charter_city) designation, as opposed to a [general law city](/General_law_city). The current charter, ratified on June 8, 1999, has undergone numerous amendments. &#91;280&#93; The city's [elected government](/List_of_elected_officials_in_Los_Angeles) comprises the [Los Angeles City Council](/Los_Angeles_City_Council) and the [Mayor of Los Angeles](/Mayor_of_Los_Angeles), operating within a [mayor–council government](/Mayor%E2%80%93council_government) framework. Additionally, the city includes the offices of the [city attorney](/Los_Angeles_City_Attorney) (distinct from the [Los Angeles County District Attorney](/Los_Angeles_County_District_Attorney), a county-level office) and the [controller](/Los_Angeles_City_Controller). The current mayor is [Karen Bass](/Karen_Bass). &#91;281&#93; The city is divided into [15 city council districts](/Los_Angeles_City_Council).

The city government encompasses numerous departments and appointed officials, including the [Los Angeles Police Department](/Los_Angeles_Police_Department) (LAPD), &#91;282&#93; the [Los Angeles Board of Police Commissioners], &#91;283&#93; the [Los Angeles Fire Department](/Los_Angeles_Fire_Department) (LAFD), &#91;284&#93; the [Housing Authority of the City of Los Angeles](/Housing_Authority_of_the_City_of_Los_Angeles) (HACLA), &#91;285&#93; the [Los Angeles Department of Transportation](/Los_Angeles_Department_of_Transportation) (LADOT), &#91;286&#93; and the [Los Angeles Public Library](/Los_Angeles_Public_Library) (LAPL). &#91;287&#93;

The City of Los Angeles charter, approved by voters in 1999, established a system of advisory neighborhood councils. These councils are intended to represent the diverse interests of stakeholders, defined as individuals who reside, work, or own property within a particular neighborhood. The neighborhood councils operate with a significant degree of autonomy and are self-determining in nature; they establish their own boundaries, bylaws, and elect their own officers. Approximately 90 such neighborhood councils are currently active.

Residents of Los Angeles elect [supervisors](/Los_Angeles_County_Board_of_Supervisors) to represent them in the 1st, 2nd, 3rd, and 4th supervisorial districts.

##### Federal and state representation

Within the [California State Assembly](/California_State_Assembly), Los Angeles is divided among fourteen districts. &#91;288&#93; In the [California State Senate](/California_State_Senate), the city's representation is split across eight districts. &#91;289&#93; In the [United States House of Representatives](/United_States_House_of_Representatives), Los Angeles is encompassed by nine congressional districts. &#91;290&#93;

